Thanks for all of your questions and a big thanks to @ErinBakerMotors for being on hand today to answer them all 👏

@Shearn7Sally Hi, Kent to Devon is on the limit of most ranges. I say stay in the comfort zone and go plug-in hybrid, so you can do most daily drives on electric (approx 30 miles) but long journeys with fuel back-up. My pick? BMW X5, Volvo XC40 or Kia Nero hybrids, depending on budget

@ace_eyed_ace Hey, we reckon they'll do neither but rather hold firm. That's because supply will be low due to factory and transport closures and demand is strong due to consumers having to wait to change cars, and others going right off health risks posed by public transport....

@RebeccaTracy1 Hi Rebecca. At the low end of budget you've got the likes of Renault Zoe, Vauxhall Corsa Electric and Nissan Leaf, then likes of Hyundai Kona, Mini E, BMW i3 and VW ID3. Then premium include Audi Etron, Tesla Model 3, S or X, and Jaguar IPace. I'd go Leaf, Mini E, Tesla3. 🙂

@johnrawlings @ErinBakerMotors Hi John, as you say, diesel deterioration shouldn't be an issue this far in. If in doubt, run the tank down on essential trips and fill with fresh. Remember not to leave a tank almost empty for long periods, to prevent condensation.
@StuartDavies50 ok my colleague says: we do see a £4k difference between trade and retail. Both valuations are tracking the markets (trade is from auctions pre shut down).

@clint_boosters Pick-up: used Mistubishi L200 (invincible), followed by Toyota HiLux. 4x4: new Dacia Duster 4WD for the price of a used Mitsu Outlander, which would be second choice (plug-in hybrid version makes sense). Subaru Forester always popular with people who actually need 4WD.

@meNYselfandi Neat idea: I like your style. Converting to electric will future-proof your Defender, but it will be pricey. Good investment though - JLR are starting to offer some bespoke conversions - see Prince Harry's wedding electric E-Type!

@victoriagods @ErinBakerMotors @AudiUK @SEATUK @UKVolkswagen insurance for 1st time drivers is a nightmare - often cost you more than the car. Choose an insurer that offers to fit black box which sends back data on how aggressive driver is. Smooth braking/accelerating/steering can lower your premiums.

@StuartDavies50 Hi, do you mean part ex? If so, my colleague says: "Part x can be good deal lower than retail. We derive our PX valuation from our trade valuation (costs & fees) and our trade valuations, in turn, are derived from our retail valuation, which is in line with retailers' pricing"

@mickb916 Hi Michael, a trickle or smart charger is optimal, but if no off-street parking, regular use is only bet really (don't try to charge it by idling: doesn't help and causes noise and pollution). If parked securely, disabling alarm helps.

@laylasmithuk @ErinBakerMotors Hi Layla, the last new diesel will be sold in 2035 (or is it 2032 - the govt keeps changing its mind), so a few more years. In practice though, they're increasingly banned from city centres, so depending on where you live, they're already so-long-and-thanks-for-all-the-fish.

@dingdongdawson Personally I'm bored of SUVs so I hope we do see that - return to the humble estate would be nice - same space and handles better! Defo predict more electric searches - heading that way anyway and now we all appreciate the planet a little more...

@AnneCarwardine Hi Anne, yes it's called a flat spot and you don't want them. But it'll be worse for your car if you start it, drive a metre and stop again. You need to take it for a little jaunt to ease pressure on tyres, brakes and engine. Once a week will do. 20-30 mins. Bob's your uncle

@wardrobefairy Hi Victoria, ah the XC90, my fave 7-seater. For a runner rail inside it you're gonna need a big SUV. So it's XC90, Land Rover Discovery, Hyundai Santa Fe, Kia Sorento (new one looks the beez kneez), Mistubishi Outlander, Merc GLS. Merc is MASSIVE.

@mrmarcusuk Hi Marcus, car dealers are set to hold their prices when this lifts because there is pent-up demand for both new and used. Supply of new is down due to factory closures and demand for used is up from those who now don't want to use public transport.

@Jennarr18 Hi Jenna, yes. Critical factor (always, not just during lockdown), is not just to pop to the shops/work/school/doctors/station in it, because a diesel engine needs to get properly warm. One round trip of 20 miles a week, is better than five trips of four miles a week.

@nigelgowling Hi Nigel. Most SUVs score max NCAP safety rating these days. What splits them is whether they have 4WD, and aids like blind-spot warning, pedestrian alert etc on low trim levels. For good value plus good safety rating, I'd go Seat Tarraco. Pure safety? Volvo XC60 or XC90.

@tabberkev Ah, man, I'm with you on this one....the short answer is there will be but nothing springs to mind right now, because the challenges of battery weight and battery price mean cheap sports cars are the last sector to get the tech... give me five while I scratch my head

@EcooterHull @JessicaRGlover @ErinBakerMotors Hi, yes, it's defo time to take electric motorbikes and scooters seriously. The challenges of limited range and weight are getting sorted, and for the daily commute, it's a sound option. I watched the electric bikes at the IoM TT...WOW!!!
@funkytownlondon Well, it's the Lamborghini Aventador partly because it really is and partly coz I sit on their female advisory board so they'd shoot me if I said anything else! In orange, please.

@flora43hotmail1 Hi Flora, smart q. No, I think we'll see the reverse: the pandemic has made people wary about public transport; 56pc of drivers who don't currently own a car are now thinking about buying one when this lifts. We've also seen more interest in motorbikes and scooters on the site.
@Shearn7Sally Hi Sally, I'm afraid it's elbow grease, and polish, as Ken here says. If bad, then T-Cut, which is a well-known scratch removal thingy, to give it its technical term.

@SandraCTWells Hi Sandra. Best solution is a trickle charger but not many people have those and you need a drive/garage. Once a week is fine, 30 mins is good - need to get the car nice and warm, especially it it's diesel, or something called the DPF will eventually clog, which is not so good.

@EllieFCousins Hi Ellie, good question! The DVLA has now said customers can do solo test drives on trade plates but the problem is most dealers' insurance requires the dealer to sit as a passenger in car. Not many are offering it. Call and get one teed up though for when this lifts!

@SamDrew_UK Hi Sam, I love a Mini, but there are some cheaper alternatives out there for that budget for your family, like a Ford Focus, Dacia Sandero, Hyundai i30, Vauxhall Corsa, Kia Rio. I'd go for reliability over style 👍

@AdeolaMosaku Hi Adeola, the big change happens in 2035, when sale of new petrol or diesel cars are banned. But lots of cities are starting to charge diesel drivers to enter. Best way to future-proof is to buy plug-in hybrid or pure electric next time round...

@church00_h Hiya, insurance for young drivers is PAINFUL cos they do tend to have more prangs. Best bet is go with an insurer that fits a black box in your car to monitor your driving, or offers lower premiums if you don't drive between certain hours. Gentle driving can lower premiums.

@sally_peltor Hi Sally, best time to buy a convertible is winter when demand is low. But right now we all need fresh air! How about a used Audi A4 Cabrio, BMW 6-Series Conv, Jag XK or Merc E-class for space, or if it's just two, a BMW Z4  or Mazda MX-5. Mega GTs like Astons cost mega bucks....

@Tam91407193 @ErinBakerMotors Hey Tam, check out some medium family SUV options: Citroen C5 Aircross, Kia Sportage, Peugeot 3008, Ford Kuga or more expensive Merc GLE, Volvo XC60. I'd bite bullet, install home charger and go plug-in hybrid. Under 20/30 miles a day, you'll only use electric!

@SionedJohnson Hi Sioned, yes, trust me - if I can do it, you can too! Go to a petrol station (you're allowed to refuel as part of essential journeys) and buy it there. About £10. It normally comes with a funnel so you can pour it in - should be by the fuel cap - don't pour into fuel tank!

@excessjeff @ErinBakerMotors Hey Jeff, short answer: yes! You'll need a home charging point; they cost about £500 but you'll recoup that money via the much lower cost of electricity v petrol, cheaper servicing etc. I have a Nissan Leaf and have never needed a public charger - just charge at home every night!

@estreeterwrites @ErinBakerMotors Hi Emily, congrats! 🥳You need sth reliable, safe, with Isofix in the back and big boot for pram system. Look at small estates for easy loading, like the Seat Leon ST, Ford Focus estate, VW Golf estate, Skoda Octavia estate. Volvo V90 gorgeous if you need looooaaaddsss of room

@omaradona7 @ErinBakerMotors Strong q! Brands had to wait for govts to get on board with charging points, incentives etc. No point making expensive cars no one buys. But now there are good EV options from Hyundai, Kia, Peugeot, Vauxhall, Renault, Nissan and others
 @Hyundai_UK @KiaUK @renault_uk  @vauxhall

@JessicaRGlover @ErinBakerMotors There's some pent-up demand right now, for sure - the rush will be in the immediate aftermath of all this, so why not monitor prices for similar cars to yours on Auto Trader in the next few weeks and see what happens!

@CatherineHutto5 @ErinBakerMotors Hi Catherine, yes it's a good idea to drive the car once a week (combine with that essential shop run?) to avoid flat battery, seized brakes, flat tyres etc...make sure though, if it's a diesel, you run it until the engine temp warms up, or the DPF (filter) might clog

The car your gran would drive, the Nissan Cherry has something honest, homely and down-to-earth about it, just like @afcbournemouth and their manager, Eddie Howe. Of all the Premier League managers, he's also probably the one your gran would invite round for tea. #afcb 🍒 https://t.co/dduKZssYTD

BumbleBee Transformer: two cars in one. One week beat Liverpool (Chevy Camaro), next get beaten by Villa (VW Beetle). And we're always changing our manager! @WatfordFC #watfordfc https://t.co/s55J4EWtaC

The Ford Escort RS Turbo. On its day, it can take on the big boys, is loads of fun but completely unpredictable and suspect reliability. Used to make a lot of noise, now widely considered to be a money pit. @WestHam #westham #COYI https://t.co/C6QT1apWpA

Like the Lambretta TV 175, it’s perfect for the upcoming Bank Holiday season. Always a bit on the margins but colourful, stylish and every couple of decades it enjoys a resurgence. @OfficialBHAFC #BHAFC https://t.co/XHoIF5JTur

Volvo's come up with some of the best ideas in modern motoring, mirroring @SouthamptonFC's regular supply of wicked players to the PL's top clubs (Bale, Walcott, Mané, Van Dijk, Lallana and, err, Ricky Lambert). The Volvo P1800 was also driven by The Saint… #SaintsFC @VolvoCarUK https://t.co/GRvywe0f9S

'The Homer': built by a company looking to recreate former glory, looks like great fun but can be a bit mental, "sounds like the world is coming to an end", inevitably led to financial ruin. @NUFC #NUFC https://t.co/9hhpGR53bo

We decided on the Citroen 2CV for @Everton. Horrible to watch, you're sure they're going to topple over and crash every time they turn a corner (change manager) but somehow, they always get to their destination of mid table, safely and in the most boring manner possible. #EFC https://t.co/pNGlMZKLHc

Like the Ford Capri, the 1970s were the heyday for @CPFC. Noisy, more than the sum of its parts, and traditional, it’s an uncomfortable place to be if it's not yours and you don't know it well. #CPFC https://t.co/vPxe64F9yf
Well, @BurnleyOfficial is clearly a Dacia Duster; cheap, scrappy and no frills, but bloody efficient and great value for money. #UTC #BurnleyFC #twitterclarets @daciauk https://t.co/4nHaQTThX0

The Renault Avantime has lots of French flair, loads of tech, is full of ideas, and oozes style. After a great start, and getting on the @BBC_TopGear cool wall, it flattered to deceive, ending up disappointing its passionate followers due to a basic lack of quality. @Arsenal #afc https://t.co/6mHGH31nZx

Some say @SpursOfficial are like the Lancia Delta Integrale. Buccaneering, freewheeling and stylish but haven't won anything for ages. A constant tale of hope and failed expectations but with the odd moment of supreme achievement. #THFC #COYS https://t.co/I4LDRAj5HQ

Like the Kia Sportage, @SheffieldUnited are honest and no-nonsense but good quality, economical and unexpectedly challenging the more established players. They’ve also picked up a few awards on the way. #SUFC @KiaUK https://t.co/V2ivodjiYg

You’ll have to go back as far as the late 50s to when @Wolves last won the league. The same time the Mini was born as a standout British classic. The Hatch punches well above its weight, competing for a top 10 spot in 2020 sales in the UK - also popular in Europe. #wolves @MINIUK https://t.co/UJTreph4eK

Just look at the Jag XJ220, it's the 90s personified. The quality of Scholes, temper of Roy Keane, speed of Kanchelskis and the verve of Giggsy. Also a bit maverick like Eric, and if all of this doesn't get you revved up, it's as gorgeous as Beckham. @ManUtd #manutd @JaguarUK https://t.co/WrJilHfLKM

Maybach was established just two years before @ChelseaFC, and now specialises in building cars for the amusement of oligarchs living in London. Daimler bought Maybach in 1960 – but didn’t properly get going until the early '00. Expensive, lavish and powerful. #ChelseaFC https://t.co/VGO7OYqdLd

We’ve compared @LCFC to the Subaru Impreza WRX. Usually mediocre and a bit bland, apart from one unbelievable example - built entirely on speed - which to this day people still can’t quite believe happened. #lcfc https://t.co/HWqffsxmxc
